<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the difference between YAML and JSON?", answer: "YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language) and JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are both data serialization formats. YAML uses indentation and whitespace to define structure, supports comments, and is generally more human-readable. JSON uses braces and brackets, is stricter in syntax, and is natively supported in JavaScript. YAML is a superset of JSON, meaning valid JSON is also valid YAML." },
  { question: "When should I use YAML instead of JSON?", answer: "YAML is preferred for configuration files where human readability matters, such as Kubernetes manifests, Docker Compose files, CI/CD pipelines (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI), and Ansible playbooks. Its support for comments makes it ideal for documented configurations. JSON is better for API data exchange, browser consumption, and machine-to-machine communication." },
  { question: "What YAML features are not available in JSON?", answer: "YAML supports comments (lines starting with #), anchors and aliases for reusing data (&anchor and *alias), multi-line strings with block scalars (| for literal, > for folded), and complex keys. JSON has none of these features. When converting YAML with these features to JSON, comments are lost, anchors are expanded inline, and multi-line strings become escaped strings." },
  { question: "Why does YAML convert 'yes' and 'no' to booleans?", answer: "In YAML 1.1, the words yes, no, on, off, true, and false are all interpreted as boolean values. This is a common source of bugs when converting to JSON. For example, a country code 'NO' for Norway would become false in JSON. To prevent this, wrap such values in quotes in your YAML: 'yes' or \"no\". YAML 1.2 only recognizes true and false as booleans." },
  { question: "Can I convert JSON back to YAML without losing data?", answer: "Yes, converting JSON to YAML preserves all data because YAML is a superset of JSON. Every JSON data type (strings, numbers, booleans, null, arrays, objects) has a direct YAML equivalent. However, the reverse is not always true: YAML comments, anchors, and tags are lost when converting to JSON since JSON has no equivalent constructs." }
]) %>

